# CSV Parser - Practical Examples

This document provides real-world examples demonstrating the CSV parser's capabilities.

## Example 1: Employee Data Processing

Process employee records with mixed data types:

```typescript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';

const employeeCSV = `
id,name,department,salary,hire_date,active
1,John Smith,Engineering,95000,2020-01-15,true
2,Jane Doe,Marketing,75000,2019-06-20,true
3,Bob Johnson,Sales,65000,2021-03-10,false
4,Alice Chen,Engineering,105000,2018-11-05,true
5,Charlie Brown,Operations,70000,2020-08-12,true
`;

const result = parseCSV(employeeCSV);

// Get all active employees
const activeEmployees = result.filter(emp => emp.active === true);
console.log(`Active employees: ${activeEmployees.length}`);

// Calculate average salary
const avgSalary = result.average('salary');
console.log(`Average salary: $${avgSalary.toFixed(2)}`);

// Group by department
const byDept = result.groupBy('department');
for (const [dept, emps] of byDept) {
  const deptTotal = emps.reduce((sum, e) => sum + e.salary, 0);
  console.log(`${dept}: ${emps.length} employees, $${deptTotal} total`);
}

// Engineering department analysis
