# CSV Parser - Practical Examples

This document provides real-world examples demonstrating the CSV parser's capabilities.

## Example 1: Employee Data Processing

Process employee records with mixed data types:

```typescript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';

const employeeCSV = `
id,name,department,salary,hire_date,active
1,John Smith,Engineering,95000,2020-01-15,true
2,Jane Doe,Marketing,75000,2019-06-20,true
3,Bob Johnson,Sales,65000,2021-03-10,false
4,Alice Chen,Engineering,105000,2018-11-05,true
5,Charlie Brown,Operations,70000,2020-08-12,true
`;

const result = parseCSV(employeeCSV);

// Get all active employees
const activeEmployees = result.filter(emp => emp.active === true);
console.log(`Active employees: ${activeEmployees.length}`);

// Calculate average salary
const avgSalary = result.average('salary');
console.log(`Average salary: $${avgSalary.toFixed(2)}`);

// Group by department
const byDept = result.groupBy('department');
for (const [dept, emps] of byDept) {
  const deptTotal = emps.reduce((sum, e) => sum + e.salary, 0);
  console.log(`${dept}: ${emps.length} employees, $${deptTotal} total`);
}

// Engineering department analysis
const engineering = result.filter(emp => emp.department === 'Engineering');
const engAvg = engineering
  .reduce((sum, e) => sum + e.salary, 0) / engineering.length;
console.log(`Engineering avg salary: $${engAvg.toFixed(2)}`);
```

## Example 2: Sales Data Analysis with Complex Filtering

Analyze sales transactions with date ranges and conditions:

```typescript
const salesCSV = `
date,product,category,quantity,unit_price,discount,total
2024-01-01,"Laptop Pro","Electronics",2,1299.99,0.1,2339.98
2024-01-02,"Mouse Pad","Accessories",50,4.99,0,249.50
2024-01-03,"USB Cable","Accessories",100,2.99,0.15,254.15
2024-01-04,"Monitor 4K","Electronics",5,599.99,0.05,2849.95
2024-01-05,"Keyboard Mechanical","Electronics",10,149.99,0,1499.90
2024-01-06,"Desk Lamp","Furniture",15,29.99,0.2,359.88
`;

const result = parseCSV(salesCSV);

// Total revenue
const totalRevenue = result.sum('total');
console.log(`Total Revenue: $${totalRevenue.toFixed(2)}`);

// Electronics revenue
const electronicsRevenue = result
  .filter(row => row.category === 'Electronics')
  .reduce((sum, row) => sum + row.total, 0);
console.log(`Electronics Revenue: $${electronicsRevenue.toFixed(2)}`);

// High-value transactions (>$500)
const highValue = result.filter(row => row.total > 500);
console.log(`High-value transactions: ${highValue.length}`);

// Products with discount
const discounted = result.filter(row => row.discount > 0);
console.log(`Products with discount: ${discounted.length}`);

// Average quantity per transaction
const avgQty = result.average('quantity');
console.log(`Average quantity: ${avgQty.toFixed(2)} units`);

// Category breakdown
const byCategory = result.groupBy('category');
console.log('\nCategory Breakdown:');
for (const [category, transactions] of byCategory) {
  const catTotal = transactions.reduce((sum, t) => sum + t.total, 0);
  const catQty = transactions.reduce((sum, t) => sum + t.quantity, 0);
  console.log(`${category}: ${transactions.length} transactions, ${catQty} units, $${catTotal.toFixed(2)}`);
}
```

## Example 3: Student Grades and Academic Analytics

Track student performance with multiple courses:

```typescript
const gradesCSV = `
student_id,student_name,course,grade,credits,completed
S001,Alice,Math,A,4,true
S001,Alice,Physics,B,3,true
S001,Alice,Chemistry,null,3,false
S002,Bob,Math,C,4,true
S002,Bob,Physics,B,3,true
S002,Bob,Chemistry,A,3,true
