# CSV Parser - Quick Start Guide

Get up and running with the CSV parser in minutes.

## Installation

### Option 1: TypeScript (Recommended for TypeScript projects)

```bash
# Copy csv-parser.ts to your project
cp csv-parser.ts /path/to/your/project/
```

Import and use:
```typescript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';
```

### Option 2: JavaScript (Node.js)

```bash
# Copy csv-parser.js to your project
cp csv-parser.js /path/to/your/project/
```

Require and use:
```javascript
const { parseCSV } = require('./csv-parser.js');
```

## 30-Second Example

```typescript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';

const csv = `name,age,city
John,30,New York
Jane,25,London`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.rows);
// Output:
// [
//   { name: 'John', age: 30, city: 'New York' },
//   { name: 'Jane', age: 25, city: 'London' }
// ]

console.log(result.count());  // 2
console.log(result.headers);  // ['name', 'age', 'city']
```

## Common Tasks

### Parse Simple CSV
```typescript
const result = parseCSV(csvString);
const data = result.rows;  // Array of objects
```

### Parse with Custom Delimiter
```typescript
// Semicolon-separated
const result = parseCSV(csvString, { delimiter: ';' });

// Tab-separated
const result = parseCSV(csvString, { delimiter: '\t' });
```

### Handle Quoted Fields
```typescript
const csv = `name,address
"Smith, John","123 Main St, Apt 4"`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);
console.log(result.rows[0].name);  // "Smith, John"
```

### Filter Data
```typescript
// Get all active users
const active = result.filter(row => row.active === true);

// Get people older than 30
const over30 = result.filter(row => row.age > 30);

// Combine conditions
const filtered = result.filter(row => 
  row.age > 25 && row.city === 'New York'
);
```

### Calculate Totals and Averages
```typescript
const sum = result.sum('price');      // Sum of price column
const avg = result.average('score');  // Average of score column
const count = result.count();         // Total rows
```

### Group Data
```typescript
const grouped = result.groupBy('city');

// Iterate through groups
for (const [city, rows] of grouped) {
  console.log(`${city}: ${rows.length} people`);
}

// Get specific group
const newYorkers = grouped.get('New York');
```

### Check for Errors
```typescript
if (result.errors.length > 0) {
  console.log('Parse errors found:');
  for (const error of result.errors) {
    console.log(`Row ${error.row}: ${error.message}`);
  }
}
```

## Real-World Example: Sales Analysis

```typescript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';
import * as fs from 'fs';

// Read CSV file
const csv = fs.readFileSync('sales.csv', 'utf-8');
const result = parseCSV(csv);

// Basic stats
console.log(`Total transactions: ${result.count()}`);
console.log(`Total revenue: $${result.sum('total')}`);
console.log(`Average sale: $${result.average('total').toFixed(2)}`);

// Sales by product
const byProduct = result.groupBy('product');
for (const [product, sales] of byProduct) {
  const revenue = sales.reduce((sum, s) => sum + s.total, 0);
  console.log(`${product}: ${sales.length} sales, $${revenue.toFixed(2)}`);
}

// Top customers
const byCustomer = result.groupBy('customer');
const customers = Array.from(byCustomer.entries())
  .map(([name, sales]) => ({
    name,
    count: sales.length,
    total: sales.reduce((s, sale) => s + sale.total, 0)
  }))
  .sort((a, b) => b.total - a.total)
  .slice(0, 5);

console.log('\nTop 5 Customers:');
for (const [i, customer] of customers.entries()) {
  console.log(`${i + 1}. ${customer.name}: $${customer.total.toFixed(2)}`);
}
```

## Type Coercion (Automatic Type Detection)

Values are automatically converted:

```typescript
// Before parsing (as CSV strings)
// "30" → 30 (number)
// "true" → true (boolean)
// "" → null (null)
// "hello" → "hello" (string)
```

Example:
```typescript
const csv = `name,active,score,notes
John,true,95,Great
Jane,false,88,`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

// result.rows[0].active is boolean true
// result.rows[0].score is number 95
// result.rows[1].notes is null

console.log(typeof result.rows[0].active);   // 'boolean'
console.log(typeof result.rows[0].score);    // 'number'
```

## Handling Quoted Fields and Special Characters

```typescript
const csv = `name,quote
"John ""The King"" Doe","He said ""Hello"""
"Jane Smith","Normal text"`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

// Escaped quotes are automatically unescaped
console.log(result.rows[0].name);   // John "The King" Doe
console.log(result.rows[0].quote);  // He said "Hello"
```

## Error Handling

The parser gracefully handles malformed data:

```typescript
const csv = `name,age,city
John,30,New York
Jane,25                    // Missing column
Bob,35,Chicago,USA`;       // Extra column

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(`Parsed: ${result.count()} rows`);
console.log(`Errors: ${result.errors.length}`);

for (const error of result.errors) {
  console.log(`Row ${error.row}: ${error.message}`);
}
```

## Integration with File System

### Reading from File
```typescript
import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';
import * as fs from 'fs';

const csv = fs.readFileSync('data.csv', 'utf-8');
const result = parseCSV(csv);

// Use result...
```

### Processing Large Files
```typescript
// Note: Current implementation loads entire file into memory
